00 singles]]\n[[Category:Eiffel 65 songs]]\n[[Category:Eurodance songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about loneliness]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Maurizio Lobina]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Australia]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Austria]]\n[[Category:Ultratop 50 Singles (Flanders) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one dance singles in Canada]]\n[[Category:European Hot 100 Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Finland]]\n[[Category:SNEP Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Germany]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Dutch Top 40 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Spain]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:1998 songs]]\n[[Category:Animated music videos]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8004:1341:eeb6:fd34:b83a:a91c:5118", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_(Da_Ba_Dee)"}
{"title_page": "Rona Moss-Morris", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:Rona Moss-Morris.jpg|thumb|King's College portrait, 2013]]\n'''Rona Moss-Morris''' is Head of [[Health Psychology]] and Chair in Psychology as Applied to Medicine at the [[Institute of Psychiatry]], [[King's College London]].<ref>[http://www.iop.kcl.ac.uk/staff/profile/default.aspx?go=13066 ''Institute of Psychiatry''(IoP) website. Institute of Psychiatry, King's College London. Retrieved 12 November 2013.]</ref> Her research investigates long-term, medically unexplained disorders such as [[chronic fatigue syndrome]] (CFS) and [[irritable bowel syndrome]] (IBS). She joined the IoP in 2011 and presented an inaugural lecture entitled \"Trials and tribulations: A journey towards integrated care for long term conditions.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcl.ac.uk/iop/news/events/2013/may/Professor-Rona-Moss-Morris-Inaugural-Lecture.aspx |title=Professor Rona Moss-Morris' Inaugural Lecture |publisher=King's College London |date=30 May 2013 |accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Academic career===\nGrowing up in South Africa, Rona studied [[occupational therapy]] at the [[University of Cape Town]], where she was awarded a BSc. She worked clinically in mental health in South Africa as an [[occupational therapist]] before immigrating in 1988 to New Zealand.<ref name=\"iop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iop.kcl.ac.uk/staff/profile/default.aspx?go=13066 |title=IoP: staff: Moss-Morris, Rona |publisher=IoP |date=15 November 2011 |accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[University of Auckland]] she studied for a Masters and PhD in health psychology. She worked there as a lecturer and whilst on the faculty helped to set up a Masters course in Health Psychology.<ref name=\"iop\" />\n\nIn 2006, Rona moved again, this time to the [[University of Southampton]] in the UK and was made Professor of Health Psychology in 2007. Here she researched, amongst other topics, the links between chronic illness and personality factors (for example the link between IBS and perfectionism<ref>{{cite news |title='Perfectionism' bowel pain link |date=26 February 2007 |work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/6387675.stm}}</ref>).\n\nShe is currently a professor at the Institute of Psychiatry in South London, where she joined the Department of Psychology in 2011.\n\n===Research===\nRona has dedicated her academic career to investigating chronic fatigue syndrome (CFS), irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) and [[post-concussion syndrome]]. This work has included attempts to model and treat<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dennison | first1 = Laura | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = Rona | year = 2010 | title = Cognitive behavioural therapy: what benefits can it offer people with Multiple Sclerosis? | journal = Expert Review of Neurotherapeutics | volume = 10 | issue = 9| pages = 1383\u20131390 | doi = 10.1586/ern.10.111 | pmid = 20819010 | url = https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/165335/1/Dennison_%2526_Moss-Morris_CBT_review_Expert_Neuro.doc }}</ref> the disorders as well as understanding psychological factors involved in reactions to chronic illness as well as how the patient<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dennison | first1 = Laura | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = Rona | last3 = Silber | first3 = Eli | last4 = Galea | first4 = Ian | last5 = Chalder | first5 = Trudie | year = 2010 | title = Cognitive and behavioural correlates of different domains of psychological adjustment in early stage multiple sclerosis | url = | journal = Journal of Psychosomatic Research | volume = 69 | issue = 4| pages = 353\u2013361 | doi = 10.1016/j.jpsychores.2010.04.009 | pmid = 20846536 }}</ref> and their family adjust to the symptoms.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bogosian | first1 = Angeliki | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = Rona | last3 = Bishop | first3 = Felicity L. | last4 = Hadwin | first4 = Julie A. | year = 2011 | title = How do adolescents adjust to their parent's multiple sclerosis?: An interview study | journal = British Journal of Health Psychology | volume = 16 | issue = 2| pages = 430\u2013444 | doi = 10.1348/135910710X521492 | pmid = 21489068 }}</ref> She has spoken at public engagement events on the relationship between stress and illness.<ref>[http://www.thepsychologist.org.uk/archive/archive_home.cfm/volumeID_24-editionID_200-ArticleID_1853 The Psychologist, volume 24, part 5 (2011)]</ref> She has developed a web-based version of a CBT Package called MSInvigor8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mssociety.org.uk/ms-research/research-blog/2012/05/can-we-manage-fatigue-better |title=Can we manage fatigue better? &#124; Multiple Sclerosis Society UK |publisher=Mssociety.org.uk |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nRona has co-authored a book with [[Keith Petrie]] entitled ''Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (Experience of Illness)''.<ref>{{citation |last=Moss-Morris |first=Rona |year=2001 |title=Chronic fatigue syndrome |last2=Petrie |first2=Keith J |publisher=Routledge |series=Experience of illness |isbn=9780203189702 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/chronicfatiguesy0000moss }}</ref>\n\nRona has contributed to over 61 academic articles in a variety of peer-reviewed journals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/rona.moss-morris.html |title=Rona Moss-Morris - Research Portal, King's College, London |publisher=King's College London |accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> The following are a selection of the few most recent:\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Chilcot | first1 = J. | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = R. | year = 2013 | title = Changes in illness-related cognitions rather than distress mediate improvements in irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) symptoms and disability following a brief cognitive behavioural therapy intervention | journal = Behaviour Research and Therapy | volume = 51 | issue = 10| pages = 690\u2013695 | doi=10.1016/j.brat.2013.07.007| pmid = 23948131 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Tamagawa | first1 = R. | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = R. | last3 = Martin | first3 = A. | last4 = Robinson | first4 = E. | last5 = Booth | first5 = R. J. | year = 2013 | title = Dispositional emotion coping styles and physiological responses to expressive writing | journal = British Journal of Health Psychology | volume = 18 | issue = 3| pages = 574\u201392 | doi=10.1111/bjhp.12004| pmid = 23126551 }}\n*Powell, D. J. H., Liossi, C., Moss-Morris, R. & Schlotz, W. (2013) Unstimulated cortisol secretory activity in everyday life and its relationship with fatigue and chronic fatigue syndrome: A systematic review and subset meta-analysis ''Psychoneuroendocrinology''\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Dima | first1 = A. | last2 = Lewith | first2 = G. T. | last3 = Little | first3 = P. | last4 = Moss-Morris | first4 = R. | last5 = Foster | first5 = N. E. | last6 = Bishop | first6 = F. L. | year = 2013 | title = Identifying patients' beliefs about treatments for chronic low back pain in primary care: a focus group study | journal = British Journal of General Practice | volume = 63 | issue = 612| pages = 490\u20138 | doi=10.3399/bjgp13x669211| pmid = 23834886 | pmc = 3693806 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Everitt | first1 = H. | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = R. | last3 = Sibelli | first3 = A. | last4 = Tapp | first4 = L. | last5 = Coleman | first5 = N. | last6 = Yardley | first6 = L. | last7 = Smith | first7 = P. | last8 = Little | first8 = P. | year = 2013 | title = Management of irritable bowel syndrome in primary care: the results of an exploratory randomised controlled trial of mebeverine, methylcellulose, placebo and a self-management website | journal = BMC Gastroenterology | volume = 13 | issue = 1| page = 68 | doi=10.1186/1471-230x-13-68| pmid = 23602047 | pmc = 3651308 }}\n\n==Awards==\nRona won MS Research of the Year as part of the [[Multiple Sclerosis Society of Great Britain|Multiple Sclerosis Society]] Awards 2013 for her randomised controlled trial ''Adjusting to MS'', which compared [[cognitive behavioural therapy|CBT]] and supportive listening to help people adjust to early stages of [[multiple sclerosis]] (MS).<ref>[http://www.mssociety.org.uk/node/670442#research MS Society website, retrieved 12th Nov 2013]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oNhP_AgOGOw Adjusting to MS: what do we know and can we help?] MS Society Talking Research video\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moss-Morris, Rona}}\n[[Category:Academics of King's College London]]\n[[Category:University of Auckland alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Auckland faculty]]\n[[Category:British psychologists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:Rona Moss-Morris.jpg|thumb|King's College portrait, 2013]]\n'''Rona Moss-Morris''' is Head of [[Health Psychology]] and Chair in Psychology as Applied to Medicine at the [[Institute of Psychiatry]], [[King's College London]].<ref>[http://www.iop.kcl.ac.uk/staff/profile/default.aspx?go=13066 ''Institute of Psychiatry''(IoP) website. Institute of Psychiatry, King's College London. Retrieved 12 November 2013.]</ref> Her research investigates long-term, medically unexplained disorders such as [[chronic fatigue syndrome]] (CFS) and [[irritable bowel syndrome]] (IBS). She joined the IoP in 2011 and presented an inaugural lecture entitled \"Trials and tribulations: A journey towards integrated care for long term conditions.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcl.ac.uk/iop/news/events/2013/may/Professor-Rona-Moss-Morris-Inaugural-Lecture.aspx |title=Professor Rona Moss-Morris' Inaugural Lecture |publisher=King's College London |date=30 May 2013 |accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Academic career===\nGrowing up in South Africa, Rona studied [[occupational therapy]] at the [[University of Cape Town]], where she was awarded a BSc. She worked clinically in mental health in South Africa as an [[occupational therapist]] before immigrating in 1988 to New Zealand.<ref name=\"iop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iop.kcl.ac.uk/staff/profile/default.aspx?go=13066 |title=IoP: staff: Moss-Morris, Rona |publisher=IoP |date=15 November 2011 |accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[University of Auckland]] she studied for a Masters and PhD in health psychology. She worked there as a lecturer and whilst on the faculty helped to set up a Masters course in Health Psychology.<ref name=\"iop\" />\n\nIn 2006, Rona moved again, this time to the [[University of Southampton]] in the UK and was made Professor of Health Psychology in 2007. Here she researched, amongst other topics, the links between chronic illness and personality factors (for example the link between IBS and perfectionism<ref>{{cite news |title='Perfectionism' bowel pain link |date=26 February 2007 |work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/6387675.stm}}</ref>).\n\nShe is currently a professor at the Institute of Psychiatry in South London, where she joined the Department of Psychology in 2011.\n\n===Research===\nRona has dedicated her academic career to investigating chronic fatigue syndrome (CFS), irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) and [[post-concussion syndrome]]. This work has included attempts to model and treat<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dennison | first1 = Laura | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = Rona | year = 2010 | title = Cognitive behavioural therapy: what benefits can it offer people with Multiple Sclerosis? | journal = Expert Review of Neurotherapeutics | volume = 10 | issue = 9| pages = 1383\u20131390 | doi = 10.1586/ern.10.111 | pmid = 20819010 | url = https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/165335/1/Dennison_%2526_Moss-Morris_CBT_review_Expert_Neuro.doc }}</ref> the disorders as well as understanding psychological factors involved in reactions to chronic illness as well as how the patient<ref>Dennison, Laura, Moss-Morris, Rona, Silber, Eli, Galea, Ian and Chalder, Trudie (2010) Cognitive and behavioural correlates of different domains of psychological adjustment in early stage multiple sclerosis. Journal of Psychosomatic Research, 69, (4), 353\u2013361. (doi:10.1016/j.jpsychores.2010.04.009) ({{PMID|20846536}})</ref> and their family adjust to the symptoms.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bogosian | first1 = Angeliki | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = Rona | last3 = Bishop | first3 = Felicity L. | last4 = Hadwin | first4 = Julie A. | year = 2011 | title = How do adolescents adjust to their parent's multiple sclerosis?: An interview study | journal = British Journal of Health Psychology | volume = 16 | issue = 2| pages = 430\u2013444 | doi = 10.1348/135910710X521492 | pmid = 21489068 }}</ref> She has spoken at public engagement events on the relationship between stress and illness.<ref>[http://www.thepsychologist.org.uk/archive/archive_home.cfm/volumeID_24-editionID_200-ArticleID_1853 The Psychologist, volume 24, part 5 (2011)]</ref> She has developed a web-based version of a CBT Package called MSInvigor8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mssociety.org.uk/ms-research/research-blog/2012/05/can-we-manage-fatigue-better |title=Can we manage fatigue better? &#124; Multiple Sclerosis Society UK |publisher=Mssociety.org.uk |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nRona has co-authored a book with [[Keith Petrie]] entitled ''Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (Experience of Illness)''.<ref>{{citation |last=Moss-Morris |first=Rona |year=2001 |title=Chronic fatigue syndrome |last2=Petrie |first2=Keith J |publisher=Routledge |series=Experience of illness |isbn=9780203189702 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/chronicfatiguesy0000moss }}</ref>\n\nRona has contributed to over 61 academic articles in a variety of peer-reviewed journals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/rona.moss-morris.html |title=Rona Moss-Morris - Research Portal, King's College, London |publisher=King's College London |accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> The following are a selection of the few most recent:\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Chilcot | first1 = J. | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = R. | year = 2013 | title = Changes in illness-related cognitions rather than distress mediate improvements in irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) symptoms and disability following a brief cognitive behavioural therapy intervention | journal = Behaviour Research and Therapy | volume = 51 | issue = 10| pages = 690\u2013695 | doi=10.1016/j.brat.2013.07.007| pmid = 23948131 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Tamagawa | first1 = R. | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = R. | last3 = Martin | first3 = A. | last4 = Robinson | first4 = E. | last5 = Booth | first5 = R. J. | year = 2013 | title = Dispositional emotion coping styles and physiological responses to expressive writing | journal = British Journal of Health Psychology | volume = 18 | issue = 3| pages = 574\u201392 | doi=10.1111/bjhp.12004| pmid = 23126551 }}\n*Powell, D. J. H., Liossi, C., Moss-Morris, R. & Schlotz, W. (2013) Unstimulated cortisol secretory activity in everyday life and its relationship with fatigue and chronic fatigue syndrome: A systematic review and subset meta-analysis ''Psychoneuroendocrinology''\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Dima | first1 = A. | last2 = Lewith | first2 = G. T. | last3 = Little | first3 = P. | last4 = Moss-Morris | first4 = R. | last5 = Foster | first5 = N. E. | last6 = Bishop | first6 = F. L. | year = 2013 | title = Identifying patients' beliefs about treatments for chronic low back pain in primary care: a focus group study | journal = British Journal of General Practice | volume = 63 | issue = 612| pages = 490\u20138 | doi=10.3399/bjgp13x669211| pmid = 23834886 | pmc = 3693806 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Everitt | first1 = H. | last2 = Moss-Morris | first2 = R. | last3 = Sibelli | first3 = A. | last4 = Tapp | first4 = L. | last5 = Coleman | first5 = N. | last6 = Yardley | first6 = L. | last7 = Smith | first7 = P. | last8 = Little | first8 = P. | year = 2013 | title = Management of irritable bowel syndrome in primary care: the results of an exploratory randomised controlled trial of mebeverine, methylcellulose, placebo and a self-management website | journal = BMC Gastroenterology | volume = 13 | issue = 1| page = 68 | doi=10.1186/1471-230x-13-68| pmid = 23602047 | pmc = 3651308 }}\n\n==Awards==\nRona won MS Research of the Year as part of the [[Multiple Sclerosis Society of Great Britain|Multiple Sclerosis Society]] Awards 2013 for her randomised controlled trial ''Adjusting to MS'', which compared [[cognitive behavioural therapy|CBT]] and supportive listening to help people adjust to early stages of [[multiple sclerosis]] (MS).<ref>[http://www.mssociety.org.uk/node/670442#research MS Society website, retrieved 12th Nov 2013]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oNhP_AgOGOw Adjusting to MS: what do we know and can we help?] MS Society Talking Research video\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moss-Morris, Rona}}\n[[Category:Academics of King's College London]]\n[[Category:University of Auckland alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Auckland faculty]]\n[[Category:British psychologists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResearch:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rona_Moss-Morris"}
